<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-570-402  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 570 402.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Business  August 21 1989 v15 n17 p40(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Wafer firms feel the squeeze. (Special Report)andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Wafer suppliers are feeling the pressure from the semiconductorindustry to provide better quality chips and better service at alower price than their competitor.andP;  Semiconductor manufacturerscan get away with such behavior because the wafer business isunderpriced for its manufacturing costs; supply and demand areabout even.andP;  Only once in the last five years have the tables beenturned: in 1984, prices skyrocketed and lead times stretched to 42weeks from the usual eight weeks.andP;  But a situation like that willlikely not occur again, especially with European wafer makersbalancing Japan's pricing policies.andP;  Two German firms, Huels andWacker Chemie GmbH claim almost 35 percent of t he world wafermarket, compared with Japan's 62 percent.andP;  Huels operates withinthe US at Monsanto's facilities under the banner MEMC ElectronicMaterials Inc.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Huels AG (acquisitions and mergers)Wacker-Chemie GmbH (management)MEMC Electronic Materials Inc. (management).andO;Topic:     Semiconductor industrySupplyPricing PolicySemiconductor Production EquipmentMarket Share.andO;Feature:   illustrationtablegraph.andO;Caption:   Merchant wafer production, 1986, 1989. (table)Merchant market shares. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>